gov.va.med.srcalc.web.view.admin

Class EditMultiSelectVar

  • java.lang.Object
    • gov.va.med.srcalc.web.view.admin.EditBaseVar
      • gov.va.med.srcalc.web.view.admin.EditMultiSelectVar
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    EditVar
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    EditExistingMultiSelectVar

    public class EditMultiSelectVar
extends EditBaseVar

    A form backing object for creating a new or editing an existing MultiSelectVariable.

    This code is tightly coupled with newMultiSelectVariable.jsp.

      • getValidator

        public EditMultiSelectVarValidator getValidator()
        Description copied from interface: EditVar

        Returns an appropriate Validator instance for validating this object.

        Implementations do not perform their own validation so that the web code can directly bind user input to these beans without fear of Exceptions. We instead provide a Spring Validator via this method to safely ensure that user input meets the underlying variable class's requirements.

      • getOptions

        public final java.util.List<java.lang.String> getOptions()
        Returns the options to set on the variable. Note that MultiSelectVariables actually have collections of MultiSelectOption, but since those objects effectively only contain Strings, we represent them as Strings here for easy use in views.
        Returns:
        a mutable List
        See Also:

      • getTrimmedOptions

        public final com.google.common.collect.ImmutableList<java.lang.String> getTrimmedOptions()

        Like getOptions() but with trailing blanks trimmed off.

        This method is useful because the HTTP form submission may create spurious trailing blank options. The form submission should not, however, create spurious blanks in the middle of the list so we consider those intentional user input and preserve them.

        Returns:
        an ImmutableList

      • getMultiSelectOptions

        protected com.google.common.collect.ImmutableList<MultiSelectOption> getMultiSelectOptions()
        Returns the options as a List of MultiSelectOption, the type needed to actually create the variable. Internally uses getTrimmedOptions() to omit any trailing blanks.
        Returns:
        an ImmutableList
